{"index": 8, "truth": "C", "prediction": "C", "is_correct": true, "raw_response": "At 90°C, the pKw of water is approximately 12.43, so Kw ≈ 3.715 × 10⁻¹³.\n\n[H⁺] = [OH⁻] = √(3.715 × 10⁻¹³) ≈ 6.095 × 10⁻⁷ mol/kg\n\nIonic strength I = ½ Σ mᵢzᵢ² = ½([H⁺]·1² + [OH⁻]·1²) = [H⁺] ≈ 6.095 × 10⁻⁷\n\nLooking at the options, the closest is 6.281 × 10⁻⁷, which corresponds to pKw ≈ 12.404 at 90°C (some sources give pKw = 12.40 at 90°C, giving [H⁺] = √(3.981 × 10⁻¹³) ≈ 6.31 × 10⁻⁷, still closest to C).\n\nActually with pKw = 12.40: Kw = 10⁻¹²·⁴⁰ = 3.981 × 10⁻¹³, [H⁺] = 6.310 × 10⁻⁷ — closest to C.\n\nWith pKw = 12.452 (NIST value at 90°C): Kw = 3.531 × 10⁻¹³, [H⁺] = 5.942 × 10⁻⁷ — closest to C still.\n\nThe answer closest to standard values at 90°C is C.\n\n<<< C >>>"}
